Sure, based on your description, a possible structure could be something along the following lines:

```json
{
    "drawing": {
        "nodes": [
            {
                "id": "node1",
                "coordinates": [x, y, z]
            },
            {
                "id": "node2",
                "coordinates": [x, y, z]
            },
            // .... more nodes
        ],
        "edges": [
            {
                "id": "edge1",
                "startNode": "node1",
                "endNode": "node2",
                "lineSegment": [[x1, y1, z1], [x2, y2, z2]]
            },
            // .... more edges
        ],
        "circles": [
            {
                "id": "circle1",
                "center": [x, y, z],
                "radius": r,
                "normal": [nx, ny, nz]    // direction normal to the circle
            },
            // .... more circles or arcs
        ]
    }
}
```

It's worth noting a few things here:

- This structure assumes each node and edge gets a unique id so they can be referenced elsewhere in the drawing.
- The "lineSegment" in each edge is represented as an array of two 3d points indicating the start and end of the edge. 
- For circles or arcs, their center, radius, and a normal is used to describe them. The normal is necessary in 3D since it specifies the plane in which the circle lies.

Please replace x, y, z, nx, ny, nz, x1, y1, z1, x2, y2, z2 and r with the actual values from your drawing. The given format is just a blueprint. 

Remember to validate JSON data before using it. You can use JSON validators available online for this task.
